sentences: She studied with Henri Berthelier at the Conservatoire de Paris, graduating in 1902.
In 1904, still a teenager, she was a soloist at the Proms concerts in London, under conductor Henry Wood.
In 1907, she toured North America as a violinist with her husband, pianist Camille Decreus, in the company of Emma Calvé.
"Madame Chemet is a violinist of great talent", explained a reviewer who heard her in Hamburg in 1911, "with great skill, splendid technique, and big (rather manly) tone.
After the war, Chemet was a soloist in Liverpool, Birmingham, Nottingham, Bradford, Cardiff, Edinburgh, and Glasgow in 1920.
In New York, she played at Carnegie Hall in 1921, at Aeolian Hall in 1923, Town Hall in 1927, and at the Metropolitan Opera House in 1925 and 1928.

Throughout the 1920s, she made many recordings, and appeared regularly on radio.
"Radio paves the way," she told a New York Times interviewer in 1930.
She played Maud Powell's violin on the radio in New York in 1925.
Chenet traveled through Hawaii to Japan in 1932, to perform with pianist Anca Seidlova and koto player Michio Miyagi.
Chemet married fellow French musician Camille Decreus in 1906.
He died in 1939.
She died in 1977, a week before her 90th birthday, in Paris.
